<WRITING SEX="MALE" PERSON="WRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Evelyn Waugh: writing</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Based on original research by members of the Orlando Project.</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KAH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>18 June 1998</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KAH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>19 October 1998</DATE><ITEM>moved 1 pub event from 18nonb-e</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>21 December 1999</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily orgName and bibCit cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="DRG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>1 February 2001</DATE><ITEM>converted textual apostrophes and quotation marks to entity references</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SLB" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 November 2002</DATE><ITEM>removed title tag(s) from workscited</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 April 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily PLACE cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 June 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily TGENRENAME cleanup, BIBCIT following P moved before P, BIBCITS TAG added</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>08 April 2005</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: March 2005 Specifications. Mainly tag/attribute name changes</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>3 March 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>28 June 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>3 January 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>4 April 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>7 April 2011</DATE><ITEM>rwt p</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>6 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>rwt c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>10 June 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 June 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>17 June 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>20 June 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>1 July 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>2 July 2011</DATE><ITEM>cas-ing and tag reports are done, but there are a few researchnotes that need answering.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>3 July 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>4 July 2011</DATE><ITEM>answered researchnotes and added bibliography entries</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>24 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>3 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>29 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>12 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb, cft c - pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="pub" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="c"><DATE>16 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Waugh, Evelyn</STANDARD><AUTHORSUMMARY><SHORTPROSE><P><GENERICRANGE>EW was a twentieth-century <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novelist</TGENRE> whose startling black humour goes together with devastating <TGENRE GENRENAME="SATIRE">satire</TGENRE> and a low estimate of unredeemed human nature (whether he is fictionalizing the failings of other people or of himself). He is remembered not only for his novels but for his prolific <TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">journalism</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="TRAVELWRITING">travel writing</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE> and <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">autobiography</TGENRE>, and for his posthumously published <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">letters</TGENRE> and <TGENRE GENRENAME="DIARY">diaries</TGENRE>.</GENERICRANGE> His resolutely unmodernised <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Catholicism</ORGNAME> and his <ORGNAME STANDARD="Conservative Party">Toryism</ORGNAME> (more social and romantic than political) were not always beneficial to his work and until well after his death inflicted serious damage to his literary reputation, making him a bugbear to a generally liberal intellectual establishment.</P></SHORTPROSE></AUTHORSUMMARY><DIV1><HEADING>Beginnings</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>EW began writing as a child. In 1985 <ORGNAME>Pilgrim Books</ORGNAME> published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Evelyn Waugh, Apprentice: The <TGENRE GENRENAME="JUVENILIA">Early Writings</TGENRE>, 1910-1927</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>During his otherwise largely wasted time as an <ORGNAME STANDARD="Hertford College,, Oxford University">Oxford</ORGNAME> undergraduate, EW had some <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short stories</TGENRE> published as well as having some success as a graphic artist.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> He put considerable effort into a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> about <TTHEMETOPIC>black magic</TTHEMETOPIC> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Temple at Thatch</TITLE> (from the eighteenth-century folly in which its <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">undergraduate hero</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> lives),</TSETTINGPLACE> <RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK DESTROYEDBY="SELF">but he destroyed it after <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL"><NAME>Harold Acton</NAME> told him that it was faulty, though promising.</RRESPONSES></RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 184, 186" DBREF="66966">184, 186</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>August 1925</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>The young EW, having recently been suicidally depressed, completed his deeply pleasurable work on <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Balance</TITLE>,</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">his first serious piece of fiction, a long, <PLITERARYSCHOOLS INVOLVEMENT="INVOLVEMENTYES">avant-garde</PLITERARYSCHOOLS> <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">story</TGENRE></QUOTE> (clearly <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">autobiographical</TGENRE>, published 1926).</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 185" DBREF="66966">185</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PANTHOLOGIZATION>Having appeared first in an anthology edited by <NAME>Alec Waugh</NAME>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Georgian Stories</TITLE>, it was not reprinted until after EW&apos;s death.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PANTHOLOGIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Its young male protagonist, <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">recently an <ORGNAME STANDARD="Oxford University">Oxford</ORGNAME> undergraduate</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, is enabled by his stupid attempt at <TMOTIF>suicide</TMOTIF> to achieve a brief, exalted feeling of being poised between life and death. <TTECHNIQUES><TGENREISSUE>The technique is experimental, drawing on the genre of <TGENRE GENRENAME="FILMTVSCRIPT">silent movies</TGENRE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 185" DBREF="66966">185</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TGENREISSUE></TTECHNIQUES></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>In 1926 EW published a thirty-page <TGENRE GENRENAME="ARTCRITICISM"><TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY">essay</TGENRE></TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">PRB</TITLE> (the <TTHEMETOPIC>Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood</TTHEMETOPIC>), about an artistic movement then fallen out of favour. <PEDITIONS>It was re-published in a luxury edition in 1982, bulked up a little with a preface by <NAME STANDARD="Sykes, Christopher Hugh">Christopher Sykes</NAME> (a great admirer of Waugh&apos;s novels) and a postscript by <NAME STANDARD="Wood, Christopher,, 1941 - 2009">Christopher Wood</NAME>.<RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: There is a Christopher Wood on the standard names list: the reference is to a copy of a book by Christopher St John which was autographed by St John and addressed to Christopher Wood in 1955. I believe this is a different Christopher Wood from the one in this document and is, I think, the art critic born in 1941. If he was the same person, he would be only 14 at the time. So this name will have to be differentiated. img: thanks, very helpful. Mariana, from library catalogues (Bodleian and OCLC) I think the one in this doc is &quot;Wood, Christopher, 1941-2009&quot; and the one mentioned in stjoch is &quot;Wood, Christopher, 1911-1990&quot;. mpo: thanks, added to authority list and regularized elsewhere</RESEARCHNOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (12 November 1982): 1253" DBREF="54246">(12 November 1982): 1253</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67012" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Rossetti: His Life and Works, 1928"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>April 1928</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EW published his first book, a generally well-reviewed <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Rossetti, Dante Gabriel">Rossetti</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>: His Life and Works</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> review by <NAME>Thomas Sturge Moore</NAME>, though prominent and lengthy, was more an essay on Rossetti than a review of the book in question, and was in any case not complimentary. Moore committed several egregious errors <PATTITUDES>which <SOCALLED>Evelyn Arthur St John Waugh</SOCALLED> promptly wrote to correct.</PATTITUDES> Moore took Waugh, from the first of his names, to be a woman, not only calling him <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Miss Waugh</QUOTE> but subjecting him to gender prejudice in likening him to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">some dainty Miss of the sixties bringing the Italian organ-grinder a penny.</QUOTE></RRESPONSES> Moore wrote <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the <QUOTE DIRECT="N">squalid</QUOTE> Rossetti</QUOTE> in such a way as to imply that the epithet was one used by Waugh, and attributed to him a preference for <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><NAME STANDARD="Morris, William">Morris</NAME>&apos;s later interminable flaccid <QUOTE DIRECT="N">grinds</QUOTE> to the best constructed narratives in English verse.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (17 May 1928): 379" DBREF="54246">(17 May 1928): 379</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (10 May 1982): 341-2" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">(10 May 1982): 341-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> repeated the same mistake about Waugh&apos;s gender in 1929, noticing <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Miss Runcible&apos;s Sunday Morning</TITLE> in a collection called <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The New Decameron</TITLE>, edited by <NAME STANDARD="Greene, Vivien">Vivienne Dayrell</NAME>, as written by <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Miss Evelyn Waugh</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (26 December 1929): 1096" DBREF="54246">(26 December 1929): 1096</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Pre-War Novels</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Decline and Fall</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="63889" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Decline and Fall, 1928"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>September 1928</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RLANDMARKTEXT><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">EW published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Decline and Fall</TITLE>, his first <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>. <RPENALTIES CENSORSHIP="CENSORSHIPYES"><TTONESTYLE>Several sexually risqu&eacute; passages</TTONESTYLE> were toned down at the request of his publishers, <ORGNAME STANDARD="Chapman and Hall">Chapman</ORGNAME>,</RPENALTIES></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PEDITIONS>but he restored them in a second edition.</PEDITIONS></RLANDMARKTEXT></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 197" DBREF="66966">197</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P> Its working title was <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Decline and Fall">Untoward Incidents</TITLE>. <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>It was rejected as obscene by <ORGNAME>Duckworth</ORGNAME> before Waugh turned to his father&apos;s firm.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS><PDEDICATION>It is dedicated <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">in Homage and Affection</QUOTE> to EW&apos;s <ORGNAME STANDARD="Oxford University">Oxford</ORGNAME> friend and mentor <NAME>Harold Acton</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Waugev, Decline prelims" DBREF="63889">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PDEDICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="IDENTIFIABLE" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">The <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">naif</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> protagonist, <TCHARACTERNAME>Paul Pennyfeather</TCHARACTERNAME>, struggling with the impossible job of <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">teaching</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> at a sub-standard prep school,</TSETTINGPLACE> is deep in <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">belated adolescent angst and self-doubt</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. He feels a kind of baffled admiration for the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>unworthy and irrepressible</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Captain Grimes</TCHARACTERNAME>, who is <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>short and balding, one-legged, accustomed to being fired from his jobs for scandalous behaviour, and wholly impervious to guilt, embarrassment, or regret</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> over any of his actions&mdash;until, that is, Grimes fakes his own <TMOTIF>suicide</TMOTIF> in order to survive elsewhere.</TPLOT> <TCHARACTERIZATION><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="IDENTIFIABLE" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">Waugh based this character on an actual colleague at the first prep-school where he was for a time a master.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 194" DBREF="66966">194</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE></TCHARACTERIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES"><NAME>Rebecca West</NAME>, reviewing this novel at its first appearance, extolled the character of Grimes as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of the world&apos;s great rogues.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 181" DBREF="66966" QTDIN="QTDINYES">181</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Critic <NAME>Bruce Stovel</NAME> has pointed out that, extraordinarily, neither West nor any other of the twenty-five reviewers of this novel during its first three years explicitly acknowledged that the scandalous actions of Grimes (who was a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">lovable bounder</QUOTE> to a commentator in 1972)<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 197, 198" DBREF="66966" QTDIN="QTDINYES">197, 198</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> consist of <TTHEMETOPIC>sexual predation on boys</TTHEMETOPIC> in the school where he teaches. The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> (which called Grimes <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a cheerful criminal . . . the one attractive character in the book</QUOTE>) had apparently no ulterior meaning in pronouncing that the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">farcical representation of a small public school . . . has its gay moments.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (27 September 1928): 685" DBREF="54246">(27 September 1928): 685</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The nearest to direct acknowledgement was a comment on <TTONESTYLE><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">salacious innuendoes, which seem perpetually about to break out into something which one would not expect to see in print.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 199" DBREF="66966" QTDIN="QTDINYES">199</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTONESTYLE></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">Not until after Waugh&apos;s diaries were serialized in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Observer</TITLE> in 1973, including a passage about the actual proclivities of Grimes&apos;s original, did criticism of the novel take this element of it on board.</RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Stovel, Bruce">Stovel</NAME> takes this as an index of Waugh&apos;s success in placing his readers in the position of both knowing and not knowing the true state of affairs.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 198-9" DBREF="66966">198-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Vile Bodies</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="63890" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Vile Bodies, 1930"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE>January 1930</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PCIRCULATION>EW&apos;s second <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Vile Bodies</TITLE>, appeared. It soon became a best-seller.</PCIRCULATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PNONBOOKMEDIA>It was filmed in 2003 as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Vile Bodies">Bright Young Things</TITLE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="IMDb" DBREF="12265"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> (its original working title, from the gilded youth who are its subject).</PNONBOOKMEDIA></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This novel features not a courtship but a <TTHEMETOPIC>failed engagement</TTHEMETOPIC>: <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">it ends with the protagonist transplanted from a realm of sophisticated parties to a bleak and terrifying battlefield (a kind of geographical transformation which EW later used to conclude other novels).</TSETTINGPLACE></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Black Mischief</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="63891" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Black Mischief, 1932"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>October 1932</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">EW published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Black Mischief</TITLE>, a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SATIRE">satirical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> set in Africa, in an imaginary island (calling itself an empire) off the coast of <PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Somalia" REG="Somaliland">Italian Somaliland</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE> <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>It was illustrated with Waugh&apos;s own drawings.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mischief prelims" DBREF="63891">prelims</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Mischief 8" DBREF="68171">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>He had written it between September 1931 and May 1932.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Mischief 312" DBREF="68171">312</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PDEDICATION>He dedicated it to a pair of aristocratic friends, Ladies <NAME STANDARD="Lygon, Mary">Mary</NAME> and <NAME>Dorothy Lygon</NAME>.</PDEDICATION> It appeared a few months before <NAME>Winifred Holtby</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Mandoa! Mandoa!: A Comedy of Irrelevance">Mandoa! Mandoa!</TITLE>, which draws material (as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Black Mischief</TITLE> was believed to do) from the coronation of <NAME STANDARD="Haile Selassie">Haile Selassie</NAME>. But in Waugh&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="PREFATORYPIECE">preface</TGENRE> to a new edition of 1962 he wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The scene of the novel was a fanciful confusion of many territories,</QUOTE> based on <PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Tanzania" REG="Zanzibar">Zanzibar</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE> as much as <PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Ethiopia" REG="Abyssinia">Abyssinia</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE> (now Ethiopia). He added: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Thirty years ago it seemed an anachronism that any part of Africa should be independent of European administration. History has not followed what then seemed its natural course.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Preface 10" DBREF="68311">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT>The man who emerges as the white protagonist of the story, <TCHARACTERNAME>Basil Seal</TCHARACTERNAME>, is in trouble with his feckless, privileged circle at home, fed up and wanting to get away, when he is invited to run the Ministry of Modernization in Azania, where the <TCHARACTERNAME>Emperor Seth</TCHARACTERNAME> has just succeeded to the throne amid confusion and bloodshed. Basil once met Seth when they were both undergraduates at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Oxford University">Oxford</ORGNAME>, and he is up for any shady deal.</TPLOT> Satire on <TTHEMETOPIC>technology</TTHEMETOPIC>, <TTHEMETOPIC>bureaucracy</TTHEMETOPIC>, and <TTHEMETOPIC>progress</TTHEMETOPIC> jostles with satire on <TTHEMETOPIC>tribalism and tradition</TTHEMETOPIC> in a cartoonist&apos;s version of Africa. Another target is <TTHEMETOPIC>birth control</TTHEMETOPIC>, boosted in slogans like <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">THROUGH STERILITY TO CULTURE</QUOTE> and (a school motto) <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">WOMEN OF TO-MORROW DEMAND AN EMPTY CRADLE.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Mischief 249" DBREF="68171">249</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Indeed, it is the introduction of birth-control to Azania which finally brings down both Seth and Basil. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">The Ministry is housed in the former empress&apos;s former oratory, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a circular building of concrete and corrugated iron, its outer walls enriched with posters from all parts of Europe and the United States advertising machinery, fashion and foreign travel,</QUOTE> standing in an open space together with a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">minor gallows</QUOTE> used for <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">such trivial, domestic <TTHEMETOPIC>executions</TTHEMETOPIC> as now and then became necessary within the royal household.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Mischief 155" DBREF="68171">155</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE> Basil loses confidence in his One-Year Plan when he finds that the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>emperor</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> has had about three million pounds worth of local <TTHEMETOPIC>currency</TTHEMETOPIC> printed and intends to print more as necessary. A letter home from a visiting Englishwoman says: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Fed doggies in market place. Children tried to take food from doggies. Greedy little wretches.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Mischief 207" DBREF="68171">207</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TPLOT>The upshot of the story is renewed <TTHEMETOPIC>civil war</TTHEMETOPIC>. Azania becomes a <TTHEMETOPIC><ORGNAME>League of Nations</ORGNAME> protectorate</TTHEMETOPIC>. Basil, having escaped with his life, gets home to find his English socialite friends have not the least interest in his African adventures.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> review observed that this <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">extravaganza</QUOTE> would confirm Waugh&apos;s status as laureate of the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">bright young people</QUOTE> who were likely to encompass most of its readers.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (13 October 1932): 736" DBREF="54246">(13 October 1932): 736</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Handful of Dust</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="63892" PLACEHOLDER="EW, A Handful of Dust, 1934"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1934-09-06" CERTAINTY="BY">By early September 1934</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">EW issued his <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Handful of Dust</TITLE>, which according to the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Oxford Dictionary of National Biography">ODNB</TITLE> is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">widely regarded as his masterpiece.</QUOTE></RRESPONSES></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (6 September 1934): 602" DBREF="54246">(6 September 1934): 602</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">Waugh traces <TCHARACTERNAME>Tony Last</TCHARACTERNAME>, like others of his protagonists, from materially and socially comfortable but spiritually arid life in <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>, out beyond the bounds of the civilized to <TTHEMETOPIC>isolation and deprivation</TTHEMETOPIC>. As the book opens, Tony has a wife, a son, and a fairly grand country house of ugly Victorian construction. His wife, however, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="adultery">is unfaithful</TMOTIF>; his <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="death of child">son is killed in a meaningless accident</TMOTIF>. He sets out for <PLACE><GEOG>Brazil</GEOG></PLACE></TSETTINGPLACE> with an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>explorer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who dies there in another meaningless accident, <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">leaving Tony to fall into the hands of a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>hermit-like <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">illiterate poly-caste</QUOTE></TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who sets him to reading <NAME STANDARD="Dickens, Charles">Dickens</NAME> aloud. As the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> reviewer concluded:</TINTERTEXTUALITY> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">He [Tony] is there still.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (6 September 1934): 602" DBREF="54246">(6 September 1934): 602</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">This reviewer, <NAME>E. E. Mavrogordato</NAME>, called the book a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">study in futility,</QUOTE> in which the author <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">set out to tell us of the extinction of feeble Tony Last; and when he has finished it would be a job to find a trace of him.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (6 September 1934): 602" DBREF="54246">(6 September 1934): 602</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Scoop</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67066" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Scoop, 1938"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1938-05-07" CERTAINTY="BY">By early May 1938</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">In <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Scoop</TITLE> (another <PLACE><AREA REG="Africa">African</AREA></PLACE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, this time about <TTHEMETOPIC>journalism</TTHEMETOPIC>), EW scored another great popular success.</TSETTINGPLACE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (7 May 1938): 313" DBREF="54246">(7 May 1938): 313</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">A mix-up of names sends <TCHARACTERNAME>William Boot</TCHARACTERNAME>, an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>ineffectual nature columnist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> for a paper called the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Beast</TITLE>, to the kingdom of Ishmaelia to report on a bloody <TTHEMETOPIC>civil war</TTHEMETOPIC>.</TSETTINGPLACE></TPLOT> The flavour of William&apos;s writing is given in a sentence from one of his articles which has achieved its own fame: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><EMPH>Feather-footed through the plashy fen passes the questing vole</EMPH>.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Scoop 19" DBREF="68314">19</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><TCHARACTERNAME>Lord Copper</TCHARACTERNAME>, <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>proprietor of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Beast</TITLE>, is so intimidating</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> that the nearest approach to disagreeing with him is to say: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Up to a point, Lord Copper.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Scoop 17" DBREF="68314">17</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> William Boot normally passes below Lord Copper&apos;s radar, but his posting to Africa leaves his <TTHEMETOPIC>incompetence</TTHEMETOPIC> exposed. <TPLOT>The <TTHEMETOPIC>scoop</TTHEMETOPIC> of the title falls undeservedly into Boot&apos;s nerveless hands and he feels nothing but relief when the credit goes to somebody else.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRECOGNITIONS>The novel was a <RRECOGNITIONNAME><ORGNAME>Book Society</ORGNAME> Choice</RRECOGNITIONNAME>.</RRECOGNITIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (7 May 1938): 313" DBREF="54246">(7 May 1938): 313</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Writing in 2010 on the influence of the media on British Prime Ministers, <NAME>Ferdinand Mount</NAME> observed: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">pretty much all you need to know about <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>newspaper proprietors</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> is contained in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Scoop</TITLE>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mount 25" DBREF="63885">25</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Non-Fiction</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>Throughout his career EW published <TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY">essays</TGENRE> and <TGENRE GENRENAME="REVIEW">reviews</TGENRE>. The latter include a warm and thoughtful welcome in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Spectator</TITLE> for <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Muriel Spark</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Comforters</TITLE></TTHEMETOPIC>, 1957, and he went on to provide quotable phrases of appreciation for several of Spark&apos;s later books.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> <PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED"><PEARNINGS>His <TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">journalistic writings</TGENRE> were often a financial lifeline,</PEARNINGS></PMOTIVES> and he contributed <TGENRE GENRENAME="INTRODUCTION">introductions</TGENRE> to works by other people. <NAME>Donat Gallagher</NAME> edited a selection of his journalism under the title <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Little Order</TITLE> in 1977, and followed it in 1984 with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Evelyn Waugh: Essays, Articles and Reviews</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> EW&apos;s non-fiction books included chiefly biography and travel-writing.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Travel Writing</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><TTONESTYLE><TGENREISSUE>EW embarked on <TGENRE GENRENAME="TRAVELWRITING">travel writing</TGENRE> with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Labels: A <PLACE><REGION REG="Mediterranean Sea">Mediterranean</REGION></PLACE> Journal</TITLE>, 1930, which sets out in breezy letter-writing style to record <TTHEMETOPIC>comfortable travel</TTHEMETOPIC> (around the <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><AREA>Middle East</AREA></PLACE> and <PLACE><AREA REG="Africa">North Africa</AREA></PLACE> as well as <PLACE><AREA REG="Europe">southern Europe</AREA></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>) rather than the misadventure and hardship which Waugh felt to be overemphased by recent writers in the <TGENRE GENRENAME="TRAVELWRITING">genre</TGENRE>.</TGENREISSUE></TTONESTYLE> In <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Remote People</TITLE>, 1931, he set down observations made during the course of a winter spent in East and Central Africa (a visit which preceded the writing of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Black Mischief</TITLE>). <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ninety-two Days</TITLE>s (covering <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Guyana" REG="British Guiana">British Guiana</GEOG></PLACE> and part of <PLACE><GEOG>Brazil</GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>) followed in early 1934. <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Waugh in <PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Ethiopia" REG="Abyssinia">Abyssinia</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE></TITLE>, 1936, is notorious for being soft on <ORGNAME STANDARD="Fascist Party"><TTHEMETOPIC>fascism</TTHEMETOPIC></ORGNAME>: <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONUNACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">its controversial support for the <TTHEMETOPIC>Italian occupation</TTHEMETOPIC> is voiced in a chapter entitled, in a wry allusion to <NAME>George Bernard Shaw</NAME>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Intelligent Woman&apos;s Guide to the Ethiopian Question</TITLE>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">Its opinions made it one of Waugh&apos;s less successful books.</RRESPONSES> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">When the Going Was Good</TITLE>, 1946, reprints what EW felt to be the best passages from these four books. It does not include anything from the equally opinionated <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Robbery Under Law: The <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><GEOG REG="Mexico">Mexican</GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC> Example</TITLE>, 1939.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (23 October 1930): 863; (5 November 1931): 864; (15 March 1934) 178; (21 December 1946): 636" DBREF="54246">(23 October 1930): 863; (5 November 1931): 864; (15 March 1934): 178; (21 December 1946): 636</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Different <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> reviewers considered <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Labels: A Mediterranean Journal</TITLE> to be pleasantly written but marred by the author&apos;s ignorance, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Remote People</TITLE> also marred by lack of real interest in the people and places visited, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ninety-two Days</TITLE> <TTONESTYLE>to have the advantages of being extremely well written and projecting an authorial personality, balanced by the disadvantage of having its eyes turned inward, rather than outwards to observe.</TTONESTYLE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (23 October 1930): 863; (5 November 1931): 864; (15 March 1934): 178" DBREF="54246">(23 October 1930): 863; (5 November 1931): 864; (15 March 1934): 178</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Another reviewer judged <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Waugh in Abyssinia</TITLE> to be extremist, unsparingly critical of the patchy and imperfect <TTHEMETOPIC>Europeanization of young Abyssinians</TTHEMETOPIC> while resolutely ignorant of their native traditions, and over-enthusiastic about the Italians. <TTONESTYLE>It conceded, however, that Waugh stood <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">head and shoulders above his neighbours for the distinction of his writing and his wit.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (7 November 1936): 900" DBREF="54246">(7 November 1936): 900</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTONESTYLE> Another found the Mexican book biassed, superficial, and mistaken in believing the Mexican character to be essentially Spanish, but it praised Waugh&apos;s searing indictment of Mexican politics.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (1 July 1939): 382" DBREF="54246">(1 July 1939): 382</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>A different kind of writing was EW&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Holy Places</TITLE>, <PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>originally an article on <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Jerusalem</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Israel" REG="Israel"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC> written to commission for <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Life</TITLE> magazine</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> and reprinted as a book in 1953. Waugh returned to an earlier topic in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A <TTHEMETOPIC>Tourist in <PLACE><AREA>Africa</AREA></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, published in 1960.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (23 January 1953): 52" DBREF="54246">(23 January 1953): 52</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Biography</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="ASCRIBED">After EW&apos;s book on <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Dante Gabriel Rossetti</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, which was connected with his early ambition to be an artist, came a number of <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biographically-oriented works</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="RELIGIOUS">which sprang from his Catholic faith</TGENRE>.</PMOTIVES> His lives of <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Edmund Campion</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, 1935, and <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Ronald Knox</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, 1959, reflect this faith. In the same way, his articles on the <TTHEMETOPIC>American Cistercian <NAME>Thomas Merton</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> (as forewords to Merton&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Elected Silence</TITLE>, 1949&mdash;in England&mdash;and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Waters of Silence</TITLE>, 1950) reflect his interest in <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">US</GEOG></PLACE> <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Catholicism</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1935-10-03" CERTAINTY="BY">By October 1935</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EW published his first historical <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE>, that of <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Edmund Campion</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, whom one of his reviewers called <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the most attractive of the <TTHEMETOPIC><ORGNAME STANDARD="Society of Jesus" REG="Jesuits">Jesuits</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC> who suffered under <NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth I, Queen">Queen Elizabeth</NAME>&apos;s penal administration.</QUOTE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (3 October 1935): 606" DBREF="54246">(3 October 1935): 606</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TTONESTYLE>Waugh emphasized that his book was popular, not scholarly.</TTONESTYLE> It opens with an account of <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth I, Queen">Elizabeth</NAME> on her <TMOTIF>deathbed</TMOTIF></TTHEMETOPIC> as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an old perjured woman, dying without comfort,</QUOTE> and reflects throughout the story its author&apos;s regret that the future history of England was Protestant, not Catholic.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (3 October 1935): 606" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">(3 October 1935): 606</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1959-10-09" CERTAINTY="BY">By early October 1959</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">EW&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE> of <TTHEMETOPIC>Monsignor <NAME>Ronald Knox</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> was an act of piety and personal friendship.</PMOTIVES></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (9 October 1959): 569" DBREF="54246">(9 October 1959): 569</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>He had already, in 1949, <TGENRE GENRENAME="EDITING">edited</TGENRE> a selection of Knox&apos;s sermons.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> said: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TTONESTYLE>It is an extremely good biography: beautifully clear, tersely written, matter-of-fact about <TTHEMETOPIC>friendships and money</TTHEMETOPIC>, never uncritical, never dull.</TTONESTYLE> In a sense, obviously, it is prejudiced, but with a good kind of prejudice: a combination of personal liking and religious sympathy</QUOTE> which leaves the reader&apos;s interpretation free rein.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (9 October 1959): 569" DBREF="54246">(9 October 1959): 569</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Short Stories</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1936-07-04" CERTAINTY="BY">By July 1936</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EW&apos;s first and only volume of <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short fiction</TGENRE> was <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><TCHARACTERNAME>Mr Loveday</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s Little Outing and Other Sad Stories</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (4 July 1936): 561" DBREF="54246">(4 July 1936): 561</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><TTONESTYLE>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> found these to be vehicles for EW&apos;s own bitterness,</TTONESTYLE> tales about people of no account who get <TTHEMETOPIC>cheated or done down by life</TTHEMETOPIC>. His wit and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sense of style</QUOTE>, it said, communicate a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">consciousness of <TTHEMETOPIC>futility</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (4 July 1936): 561" DBREF="54246">(4 July 1936): 561</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>More Novels and Novellas</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Put Out More Flags</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="63893" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Put Out More Flags, 1942"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1942-03-21" CERTAINTY="BY">By late March 1942</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PDEDICATION>EW dedicated his <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Put Out More Flags</TITLE> (about the early stages of <TTHEMETOPIC><TOPIC>World War Two</TOPIC>, dubbed <SOCALLED>the phoney war</SOCALLED></TTHEMETOPIC> for their anticlimactic progress), to <NAME>Randolph Churchill</NAME>, who had secured him an army commission.</PDEDICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (21 March 1942): 137" DBREF="54246">(21 March 1942): 137</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This book brings together, in the untried and abnormal conditions of wartime, several characters from earlier novels by Waugh. <TCHARACTERNAME>Basil Seal</TCHARACTERNAME>, for instance, manages to turn an <TTHEMETOPIC>illegal profit</TTHEMETOPIC> out of the <TTHEMETOPIC>billetting of evacuee children</TTHEMETOPIC>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> review seriously considered the possibility that Waugh might be damaging his country by his descriptions of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">pathological vagaries</QUOTE> among those in charge and the chaos they produce, but decided that readers would not be influenced for ill.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (21 March 1942): 137" DBREF="54246">(21 March 1942): 137</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Work Suspended</TITLE></HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMODEOFPUBLICATION PUBLICATIONMODE="LIMITEDEDITION">Before the end of 1942 EW published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Work Suspended">Work Suspended. Two Chapters of an Unfinished <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">Novel</TGENRE></TITLE> in a limited edition of <PPRESSRUN>500 copies</PPRESSRUN>,</PMODEOFPUBLICATION> <RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK DESTROYEDBY="OTHER">with the explanation that the intervention of the war had prevented his finishing what would have been his best writing, because the world of which he had written here had vanished forever.</RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK> <PEDITIONS>In 1948 this work re-appeared as the title element in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Work Suspended">Work Suspended, and Other <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">Stories</TGENRE> written before the Second World War</TITLE>, and this was later re-issued in different forms with different sub-titles.</PEDITIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (January 1943): 41" DBREF="54246">(23 January 1943): 41</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">At the first appearance of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Work Suspended</TITLE> the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> professed itself (using slightly more polite terms than these) unable to see what all the fuss was about.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (January 1943): 41" DBREF="54246">(23 January 1943): 41</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Brideshead Revisited</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="63894" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Brideshead Revisited, 1945"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>28 May 1945</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RBESTKNOWNWORK><PCIRCULATION>EW&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Brideshead Revisited</TITLE> appeared: his most serious fiction to date, confronting <TTHEMETOPIC>spirituality</TTHEMETOPIC>, <TTHEMETOPIC>death</TTHEMETOPIC>, and <TTHEMETOPIC>mortal sin</TTHEMETOPIC>, but also eulogizing an <TTHEMETOPIC>upper-class, country-house life</TTHEMETOPIC> which seemed about to disappear</PCIRCULATION></RBESTKNOWNWORK></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Today in Literature, 28 May 2008" DBREF="48925">28 May 2008</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Its full title is <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Brideshead Revisited">Brideshead Revisited: The Sacred and Profane Memories of Captain <TCHARACTERNAME>Charles Ryder</TCHARACTERNAME></TITLE>; <PDEDICATION>EW dedicated it to his <NAME STANDARD="Waugh, Laura">wife</NAME>.</PDEDICATION> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS><PEDITIONS>He wrote it, he explained in a <TGENRE GENRENAME="PREFATORYPIECE">preface</TGENRE> to a radically revised edition of 1959,</PEDITIONS> during injury leave from his active service in the Second World War, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a bleak period of present privation and threatening disaster . . . of soya beans and Basic English</QUOTE> which influenced him to write of food and wine in <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">rhetorical and ornamental language.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Brideshead, Preface 9" DBREF="68346">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PATTITUDES>He wrote, therefore, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">with a zest that was quite strange to me and also with impatience to get back to the war.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Brideshead, Preface 9" DBREF="68346">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PATTITUDES>In 1959 he observed that he had some doubts about the form of the novel, but would make no apology for the perhaps presumptuous theme:</PATTITUDES> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the <TTHEMETOPIC>operation of divine grace</TTHEMETOPIC> on a group of diverse but closely connected characters.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Brideshead, Preface 9" DBREF="68346">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PNONBOOKMEDIA>This novel became a highly successful television series in 1981, which added to its fame. A film made of it in 2008 proved less popular.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="IMDb" DBREF="12265"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PNONBOOKMEDIA></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TVOICENARRATION><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="UPPERCLASS">The viewpoint here is that of the narrator, <TCHARACTERNAME>Charles Ryder</TCHARACTERNAME>, as he looks back nostalgically from his current army milieu to the vanished privilege of an English country house and an <ORGNAME STANDARD="Oxford University">Oxford</ORGNAME> college. Ryder is almost forty and no longer feels romantic about the army, when his next posting turns out to be to a requisitioned country house, Brideshead, which was a key experience in his life twenty years before.</TSETTINGPLACE> As an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE><ORGNAME STANDARD="Oxford University">Oxford</ORGNAME> undergraduate</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> embarked on an intellectual but socially undistinguished career, an admirer of <NAME>Roger Fry</NAME>, he was bowled over by the fey charm of <TCHARACTERNAME>Sebastian Flyte</TCHARACTERNAME> (Lord Sebastian, since his father, <TCHARACTERNAME>Lord Marchmain</TCHARACTERNAME>, is a marquess), who is hardly ever seen without his <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>teddy bear</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Aloysius</TCHARACTERNAME>. Sebastian takes Charles to visit his family, whose most important characteristic is not their <TTHEMETOPIC>aristocracy</TTHEMETOPIC> but their <TTHEMETOPIC><ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Catholicism</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC>.</TVOICENARRATION></P><P>Lord Marchmain, who is <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>not a cradle Catholic but a convert</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, has lapsed again when he <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="adultery">left his wife to live in sin</TMOTIF> in Italy. Lady Marchmain and the eldest son, <SOCALLED>Bridey</SOCALLED> for <TCHARACTERNAME>Lord Brideshead</TCHARACTERNAME> (the title belonging to the heir), are <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>intensely devout</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, as is a younger sister, Cordelia. Sebastian is beset with problems beneath his charisma, and is rapidly developing into an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>alcoholic</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. Another sister, Julia, seems like a female version of Sebastian (which makes her sex appear her dominant characteristic). The <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">agnostic or religiously uneducated</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> Charles, who lives in a state of courteous warfare with his widower father, falls in love with the entire family.</P><P>Catholicism does not prevent the Flyte family falling into disasters, but it offers <TTHEMETOPIC>redemption</TTHEMETOPIC>. Charles and Julia fall in love, but not before each of them has married and eventually been <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="divorce">divorced</TMOTIF>. Julia&apos;s husband was the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>rich, ambitious Canadian</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Rex Mottram</TCHARACTERNAME>. Sebastian hits rock bottom and attaches himself to a monastery where he does cleaning and menial tasks between his drinking sprees and is much loved. Lord Marchmain, now a widower, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="illness">comes home gravely ill</TMOTIF> and bringing his <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>mistress</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> with him. The family gather round, and wait <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="penitence">to see if he will repent and die in the bosom of the Catholic Church. This he does.</TMOTIF> When the priest blesses him and touches his forehead with holy oil he makes the sign of the cross. From Charles&apos;s <TTHEMETOPIC>prayers</TTHEMETOPIC> we are to deduce that he too has been <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="conversion, religious">converted to belief</TMOTIF>, and he takes it calmly when Julia tells him that they cannot after all marry, since that would be <TTHEMETOPIC>mortal sin</TTHEMETOPIC>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRECOGNITIONS>This novel was a <RRECOGNITIONNAME><ORGNAME>Book Society</ORGNAME> choice</RRECOGNITIONNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRECOGNITIONS> <PCIRCULATION>It brought Waugh <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">hundreds of thousands of new American readers,</QUOTE> and, astonishingly to him, fan-mail.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 182" DBREF="66966">182</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PCIRCULATION> <PPERIODICALPUBLICATION><PATTITUDES>In early 1946 <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Life</TITLE> magazine carried his <TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY">article</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Fan-Fare</TITLE>, <TCHARACTERIZATION>in which he replied to readers who asked if he found his characters in life: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">My problem has been to distill comedy and sometimes tragedy from the knockabout farce of people&apos;s outward behaviour</QUOTE>&mdash;which in the raw, he wrote, was often too incredible for fiction.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 183" DBREF="66966" QTDIN="QTDINYES">183</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION></PATTITUDES></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">This book has been so uniformly praised that it is now surprising to see that a reviewer of Waugh&apos;s next novel, in 1948, called <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Brideshead Revisited</TITLE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">rather unsatisfactory, rather flabby.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (20 November 1948): 652" DBREF="54246">(20 November 1948): 652</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>False Starts?</HEADING><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE"><DATE>2 October 1945</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EW recorded in his <TGENRE GENRENAME="DIARY">diary</TGENRE> beginning to write a back story for <TCHARACTERNAME>Charles Ryder</TCHARACTERNAME> of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Brideshead Revisited</TITLE>. Apparently intended as a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">Charles Ryder&apos;s Schooldays</TITLE>, it became a chapter or <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">story</TGENRE> called <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Ryder by Gaslight</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (5 March 1982): 255" DBREF="54246">(5 March 1982): 255</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY>This chapter went to his typist and went to his agent (<NAME STANDARD="Peters, August Detlof">A. D. Peters</NAME>), but seems to have gone no further. The typescript was discovered among his papers years later.</PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY> It draws both on EW&apos;s diaries and on material about Ryder which was later excised from early drafts of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Brideshead Revisited</TITLE>. <PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>The typescript was published in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> in 1982.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (5 March 1982): 255" DBREF="54246">(5 March 1982): 255</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>EW&apos;s next fiction was a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVELLA">novella</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Scott-King&apos;s Modern Europe</TITLE>, 1947. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">Its protagonist, an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">obscure English schoolmaster</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, is invited to a totalitarian country to participate in <TTHEMETOPIC>tercentenary celebrations of the national poet</TTHEMETOPIC>, who is his research subject.</TSETTINGPLACE> Waugh here turns his satirical eye on <TTHEMETOPIC>political intrigue and official hospitality</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (20 December 1947): 657" DBREF="54246">(20 December 1947): 657</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Loved One</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68506" PLACEHOLDER="EW, The Loved One, 1948"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1948-11-20" CERTAINTY="BY">By late November 1948</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>EW&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> or <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVELLA">novella</TGENRE><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Loved One, The">The Loved One: An Anglo-American Tragedy</TITLE> first appeared as a single issue of <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Horizon</TITLE>.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (20 November 1948): 652" DBREF="54246">(20 November 1948): 652</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">Here EW puts his visits to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Hollywood</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="California"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE> to use in a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SATIRE">satire</TGENRE> on Californian <TTHEMETOPIC>funeral customs</TTHEMETOPIC> and what they imply of commitment to <TTHEMETOPIC>materialism and denial of spirituality</TTHEMETOPIC>.</TSETTINGPLACE> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">The story revolves around the Whispering Glades funeral parlour and cemetery,</TSETTINGPLACE> and involves a <TTHEMETOPIC>love-triangle</TTHEMETOPIC>: the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>bourgeois, emotionless mortician</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Mr Joyboy</TCHARACTERNAME>, the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">beautiful young Greek-American Aim&eacute;e (a cosmetician</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> at Whispering Glades), and <TCHARACTERNAME>Dennis Barlow</TCHARACTERNAME>, a young, English, <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>failed scriptwriter</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who has turned to the business of <TTHEMETOPIC>burying pets</TTHEMETOPIC> instead (at the Happier Hunting Grounds) but who comes to visit Whispering Glades since a yet more unsuccessful scriptwriter friend has committed <TMOTIF>suicide</TMOTIF>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> welcomed this as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">most mature and most awe-inspiring <TGENRE GENRENAME="SATIRE">satire</TGENRE>. . . . a short piece of coruscating brilliance.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (20 November 1948): 652" DBREF="54246">(20 November 1948): 652</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Early Christianity</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="68505" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Helena, 1950"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1950-10-13" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid October 1950</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">EW published an entirely new departure for him, a <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Helena</TITLE>, about the <NAME STANDARD="Helena, Empress">mother</NAME> of the <NAME STANDARD="Constantine,, Emperor of Constantinople">Emperor Constantine</NAME>, who <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="conversion, religious">converted</TMOTIF> her son to <ORGNAME>Christianity</ORGNAME> and is said to have discovered the cross on which Christ died.</TSETTINGDATE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (13 October 1950): 641" DBREF="54246">(13 October 1950): 641</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">This book traces Helena from her girlhood in <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> as the daughter of a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Romanized British landowning family</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>,</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> through her marriage to an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>ambitious young Roman officer,</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> to her successful search, as a widow, for the <TTHEMETOPIC>True Cross on which <NAME STANDARD="Jesus">Christ</NAME> was crucified</TTHEMETOPIC>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The reviewer for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> was <NAME STANDARD="Powell, Anthony Dymoke">Anthony Powell</NAME>, who gave a sympathetic account of the book but noted that the topic had taken all the author&apos;s <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">ingenuity to weld into a workmanlike novel,</QUOTE> that a jerkiness in the narrative caused the reader occasional uneasiness, and that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the final impression is not one of entire satisfaction.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (13 October 1950): 641" DBREF="54246">(13 October 1950): 641</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL"><PATTITUDES>EW&apos;s first biographer called the tepid reception of this book <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the greatest disappointment</QUOTE> in his <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">whole literary life.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>A Trilogy</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67025" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Men at Arms, 1952"></TEXTSCOPE><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67026" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Officers and Gentlemen, 1955"></TEXTSCOPE><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67525" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Unconditional Surrender, 1961"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1952-09-12" CERTAINTY="BY">By 12 September 1952</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">EW published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Men at Arms</TITLE>, the first of what became a trilogy of <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> about the <TOPIC>Second World War</TOPIC>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Sword of Honour</TITLE>. <TCHARACTERIZATION>In these novels actual people and places are <TGENRE GENRENAME="ACLEF">thinly disguised</TGENRE>.</TCHARACTERIZATION></TSETTINGDATE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (12 September 1952): 593" DBREF="54246">(12 September 1952): 593</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>When he published a second book about the army service of the same hero or anti-hero in 1955 as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Officers and Gentlemen</TITLE>, EW thought of this as having completed the series. But he then followed it with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Unconditional Surrender</TITLE> in 1961. <PDEDICATION><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Officers and Gentlemen</TITLE> is dedicated to <NAME STANDARD="Laycock, Robert">Major-General Sir Robert Laycock, K.C.M.G., C.B., D.S.O.</NAME>, with the claim that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">this story [is] pure fiction . . . . No unit, formation, command, organization, ship or club, no incident, civil or military, is identifiable with the realities of those exhilarating days when he led and I lamely followed.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Officers prelims" DBREF="68172">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Unconditional Surrender</TITLE> is dedicated to the author&apos;s daughter Margaret.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Unconditional prelims" DBREF="67525">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PDEDICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The protagonist of these books, <TCHARACTERNAME>Guy Crouchback</TCHARACTERNAME>, is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">middle-aged Roman Catholic</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="divorce">divorced</TMOTIF> from his wife, Virginia (though not in the eyes of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Church</ORGNAME>, which therefore does not regard a sexual fling with her as adultery or sin), socially alienated, and <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="retirement">physically self-isolated</TMOTIF>. He is appalled by the <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Ribbentrop, Joachim Von">Ribbentrop</NAME>-<NAME STANDARD="Molotov, Viacheslav Mikhailovich">Molotov</NAME> pact, which he sees as the uniting of the world&apos;s two great evils,<ORGNAME STANDARD="Fascist Party"> fascism</ORGNAME> and <ORGNAME STANDARD="Communist Party">communism</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC>. When war duly follows, he manages, not without difficulty, to join the <TTHEMETOPIC>army</TTHEMETOPIC>, and goes through the same process of romance followed by disillusionment that Waugh himself had experienced with <TTHEMETOPIC>military life</TTHEMETOPIC>. In Guy&apos;s world nothing is as it seems, moral issues are swathed in layers of deception, and his <TTHEMETOPIC>old-fashioned ideals of integrity and honour</TTHEMETOPIC> seem to have no purchase on actuality. The first book, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Men at Arms</TITLE>, is dominated by a comic character: the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>eccentric, old-world, probably dipsomaniac</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Apthorpe</TCHARACTERNAME>, whose death Guy may or may not have caused by giving him a bottle of whisky.</P><P><TTONESTYLE><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Officers and Gentlemen</TITLE> opens with the <TTHEMETOPIC>bombing of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>, treated as black comedy:</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE></TTONESTYLE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">On the pavement opposite Turtle&apos;s [a gentlemen&apos;s club, which is on fire] a group of progressive novelists in fireman&apos;s uniform were squirting a little jet of water into the morning-room.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Officers 3-4" DBREF="68172">3-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In another club <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><QUOTE DIRECT="N">There&apos;s a fellow under the billiard-table now.</QUOTE> <QUOTE DIRECT="N">One of the servants?</QUOTE> <QUOTE DIRECT="N">Not one I&apos;ve ever seen before.</QUOTE></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Officers 6" DBREF="68172">6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The man under the table turns out to be an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Air Marshal</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> meticulously following the instructions for <TTHEMETOPIC>air-raids</TTHEMETOPIC> which everyone else ignores. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">The book ends with the fall of <PLACE><REGION>Crete</REGION><GEOG REG="Greece"></GEOG></PLACE> at the end of May 1941 and its aftermath. Guy&apos;s men, following orders and waiting to <TTHEMETOPIC>surrender</TTHEMETOPIC>, are <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">bombed and machine-gunned</TMOTIF> in his sight, as he and a few others make a crazy attempt to escape by open boat.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> Guy is badly wounded. Recovering in hospital, he learns that <TCHARACTERNAME>Ivor Claire</TCHARACTERNAME> (whom he particularly admired as a chivalric ideal) disgracefully saved his skin during the evacuation, and that Guy&apos;s diary, which he kept even during the final excruciating stages of the retreat, has evidence to disprove Ivor&apos;s self-justifying excuse for his actions. In the end Guy betrays his Cretan experience by burning his diary. As well, though unintentionally, he fails to deliver the identity disc of a dead, Catholic soldier to the man&apos;s next of kin.</P><P><TPLOT><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Unconditional Surrender</TITLE> has a fairly busy personal plot. Guy passes milestones (his fortieth birthday, his father&apos;s death) not directly related to the war. He marks time for two years at a desk job, since his courageous exploits of the past have counted not for but against his record. While recovering from a wound he has a brief reunion with his wife, or ex-wife, Virginia (who has had two more husbands since Guy), which results in the birth of a baby boy. When Guy sees action again,</TPLOT> <TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">it is in another scene of <TTHEMETOPIC>chaos and disintegration</TTHEMETOPIC>: <PLACE><GEOG>Yugoslavia</GEOG></PLACE>, where he finds that his <TTHEMETOPIC>military, patriotic duty</TTHEMETOPIC> is to help establish an <TTHEMETOPIC>anti-religious, communist regime</TTHEMETOPIC> which is loathsome to him. He hears of Virginia&apos;s <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">death at home by bombing</TMOTIF> and arranges, speaking Latin, for a Croatian priest to say a <TTHEMETOPIC>mass for the repose of her soul</TTHEMETOPIC>. Less successfully, he attempts to help or <TMOTIF>rescue</TMOTIF> just a few of the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Jewish displaced persons</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who seem likely to spend the rest of their lives behind wire. Even the relatively sympathetic <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Commandant of an interim camp</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> says to Guy&apos;s enquiries: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">aren&apos;t you making rather heavy weather of it? What do two more or less matter?</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="EW, Unconditional 303" DBREF="67525">303</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="happy ending">Guy himself, stripped of his illusions and his <TTHEMETOPIC>ambition for honour</TTHEMETOPIC>, seems to reach happiness, married to a second wife, with two more baby boys to add to Virginia&apos;s son, managing the home farm on his family estate (of which the big house is now occupied by a convent).</TMOTIF></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Responses to the series varied widely. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Powell, Anthony Dymoke">Anthony Powell</NAME> welcomed the first of the trilogy in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE>, <TTONESTYLE>noting that it combined its serious portrayal of a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">middle-aged civilian caught up in war</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and military life with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">passages as funny as anything since <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Decline and Fall</TITLE>.</QUOTE></TTONESTYLE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (12 September 1952): 593" DBREF="54246">(12 September 1952): 593</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Among reviewers of later books by Waugh, <NAME>R. G. G. Price</NAME> supposed in 1957 that <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Sword of Honour</TITLE> possessed no higher value than <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an amiable readability,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (19 July 19530): 437" DBREF="54246">(19 July 1957): 437</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> but <NAME>John William Mills Willett</NAME> in 1961 asserted that the same novel was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">grossly under-appreciated</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (27 October 1961): 770" DBREF="54246">(27 October 1961): 770</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Willett also pronounced the trilogy as a whole to be <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the one piece of English fiction about the 1939-45 War which is certain to survive.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (27 October 1961): 770" DBREF="54246">(27 October 1961): 770</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Dystopia</HEADING><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1953-06-05" CERTAINTY="BY">By early June 1953</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TGENREISSUE><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="FUTURE"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">EW set his <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> or <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVELLA">novella</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love among the Ruins</TITLE> in an imaginary future, with a state-run society called Satellite City, a Ministry of Rest and Culture, and a <TTHEMETOPIC>Euthanasia</TTHEMETOPIC> Centre with long queues outside for its services.</TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE></TGENREISSUE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (5 June 1953): 361" DBREF="54246">(5 June 1953): 361</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The novel&apos;s title is that of a poem by <NAME>Robert Browning</NAME>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Ordeal of Gilbert Pinfold</TITLE></HEADING><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1957-07-19" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid-July 1957</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EW&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Ordeal of <TCHARACTERNAME>Gilbert Pinfold</TCHARACTERNAME></TITLE>, about a middle-aged man suffering from <TTHEMETOPIC>hallucinations</TTHEMETOPIC>, was courageously based on experiences of his own.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (19 July 1957): 437" DBREF="54246">(19 July 1957): 437</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>He began it in <PLACE><GEOG>Jamaica</GEOG><AREA REG="Caribbean"></AREA></PLACE> in January 1955.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Called by the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fantasticated <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">autobiography</TGENRE></QUOTE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (19 July 1957): 437" DBREF="54246">(19 July 1957): 437</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> this book has a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>middle-aged novelist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> as its central figure. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">While on a cruise for his health he begins to hear <TTHEMETOPIC>voices of conspirators and persecutors</TTHEMETOPIC></TSETTINGPLACE>: Trying desperately to make sense of what he hears, he thinks at first that he is eavesdropping on some extraordinary plot, then that he is the person the plotters are after. A <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Catholic priest</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who specialises in <TTHEMETOPIC>paranormal psychology</TTHEMETOPIC> (called in by the sufferer&apos;s wife) assures him that the voices all belong to himself. The reader is likely to conclude that they are <TTHEMETOPIC>hallucinations produced by prescription drugs: chloral and bromide</TTHEMETOPIC>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> called the opening chapter <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">much the best thing that has ever been written</QUOTE> about Waugh himself. This review paid tribute to him as author of a number of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">obstinately vital minor classics,</QUOTE> while adopting a grudging tone about this book and denigrating him in general as a writer with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">nothing much to say.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (19 July 1957): 437" DBREF="54246">(19 July 1957): 437</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME>Martin Stannard</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Oxford Dictionary of National Biography">ODNB</TITLE> was more representative of later opinion in admiring this book for its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">ruthlessly honest self-portrait,</QUOTE> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">while noting that many initial reviewers were shocked by the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">cold intimacy of these revelations.</QUOTE></RRESPONSES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Last Fiction</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67526" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Basil Seal Rides Again, or The Rake&apos;s Regress, 1963"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1963-11-14" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid November 1963</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PMODEOFPUBLICATION PUBLICATIONMODE="LIMITEDEDITION">EW published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVELLA">novella</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><TCHARACTERNAME>Basil Seal</TCHARACTERNAME> Rides Again, or, The Rake&apos;s Regress</TITLE> in a limited edition of <PPRESSRUN>750 copies</PPRESSRUN></PMODEOFPUBLICATION> <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>on handmade paper, with a coloured lithograph by <NAME>Kathleen Hale</NAME> as frontispiece.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (14 November 1963): 921" DBREF="54246">(14 November 1963): 921</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>EW&apos;s own chosen title was relegated to subtitle by his publishers.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TCHARACTERIZATION>Waugh here resuscitated (but transformed) a character he had introduced in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Black Mischief</TITLE> as an opportunist and developed in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Put Out More Flags</TITLE> into a spiv and swindler. Basil Seal is here (according to the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> reviewer) <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>bloated, pompous old buffer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>,</QUOTE> crusty and florid, who uses unforgivable deceit to break up his daughter&apos;s engagement.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (14 November 1963): 921" DBREF="54246">(14 November 1963): 921</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RSELFDESCRIPTION>Waugh called the book a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">senile attempt to recapture the manner of my youth</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (14 November 1963): 921" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">(14 November 1963): 921</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION> (an attempt which many admirers of his early style had been pressing him to make). <RRESPONSES>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> called it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a nasty little book</QUOTE> and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a very rum effort all round.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (14 November 1963): 921" DBREF="54246">(14 November 1963): 921</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Oxford Dictionary of National Biography">ODNB</TITLE> claimed that Waugh here portrayed with his usual startling honesty his own <TTHEMETOPIC>jealousy</TTHEMETOPIC> over the forthcoming marriage of his daughter Margaret.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Attack and Defence</HEADING><DIV2><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL">During his later life reviewers and commentators were hard on Waugh,</RRESPONSES> and he responded pugnaciously. <RPENALTIES>When <NAME>Nancy Spain</NAME> wrote rudely about him after a hostile encounter in <DATE>June 1955</DATE>,</RPENALTIES> <PEARNINGS>he sued for libel and was awarded two thousand pounds. He got half as much again when he sued <ORGNAME STANDARD="Beaverbrook">Beaverbrook Newspapers</ORGNAME> over reprinted extracts</PEARNINGS> from <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME>Rebecca West</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Meaning of Treason</TITLE>. This book, about the pro-Nazi broadcasters <NAME>William Joyce</NAME> and <NAME>John Amery</NAME>, was first published in the USA in 1947, issued in England in <DATE VALUE="1949-09-09">1949</DATE>, and several times revised.</RRESPONSES> West, who wrote harshly here about Waugh, had been one of the first to praise him as a novelist, a generation before this.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Life-Writing</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="63895" PLACEHOLDER="EW, A Little Learning, 1964"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1964-09-10" CERTAINTY="BY">By early September 1964</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE"><PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY>Approaching the end of his life, EW published an <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">autobiography</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Little Learning</TITLE> (whose title comes from <NAME>Alexander Pope</NAME>, recommending either substantial learning or none at all).</PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY></TINTERTEXTUALITY></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (10 September 1964): 836" DBREF="54246">(10 September 1964): 836</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>It was subtitled <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The First Volume of an Autobiography,</QUOTE> but no more were produced.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (10 September 1964): 836" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">(10 September 1964): 836</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Waugh presents himself as having been born into a world of beauty and preparing to die amid ugliness, an exile from the conditions of his childhood and youth.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (10 September 1964): 836" DBREF="54246">(10 September 1964): 836</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Having described his <TTHEMETOPIC>public-school and university life</TTHEMETOPIC>, he ends the book with his youthful failed <TMOTIF>suicide</TMOTIF> attempt. <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">As he tells it, he went down to the beach without a towel, left a line from <NAME>Euripides</NAME> as a suicide note, and swam out to sea, thinking of himself as a lad from the lyrics of <NAME>A. E. Housman</NAME>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> But being stung by jellyfish changed his mind: he swam back, tore up Euripides, and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">climbed the sharp hill that led to all the years ahead. </QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 192" DBREF="66966">192</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PNONSURVIVAL TYPEOFNONSURVIVAL="UNKNOWN">EW began a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SEQUEL">sequel</TGENRE> to his volume of <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">autobiography</TGENRE>, entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">A Little Hope</TITLE>, but although he worked on it for the rest of his life he left only a few pages in the roughest of drafts.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 193-4" DBREF="54246">193-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PNONSURVIVAL></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="63896" PLACEHOLDER="EW, The Diaries of Evelyn Waugh, 1976"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1976-09-03" CERTAINTY="BY">By September 1976</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The <TGENRE GENRENAME="DIARY">Diaries</TGENRE> of <NAME>Evelyn Waugh</NAME></TITLE> were posthumously published, edited by <NAME>Michael Davie</NAME>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (3 September 1976): 1074" DBREF="54246">(3 September 1976): 1074</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Waugh had begun keeping a diary as an adolescent, <RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK DESTROYEDBY="SELF">but he evidently destroyed those parts that covered his years at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Oxford University">Oxford</ORGNAME>. Also missing from the extant diary are any account of the end of his first marriage, his conversion, or his breakdown in 1954.</RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK> <PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM">Passages were serialized in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Observer</TITLE> in 1973, well before book publication.</PSERIALIZATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stovel 189, 198" DBREF="66966">189,198</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PARCHIVALLOCATION>The manuscripts were sold by his widow to the <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of Texas at Austin">University of Texas</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Austin</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Texas"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PARCHIVALLOCATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">His son <NAME STANDARD="Waugh, Auberon">Auberon</NAME> observed that crucial aspects of his father&apos;s character, his <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">spontaneous gaiety or sweetness of nature</QUOTE> with friends and his <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">kindliness, or . . . sudden disarming gentleness</QUOTE> with family, go unrecorded in his diaries.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="63897" PLACEHOLDER="EW, The Letters of Evelyn Waugh, 1980"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1980-10-17" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid October 1980</DATE><CHRONPROSE>A volume of EW&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">letters</TGENRE>, edited by <NAME>Mark Amory</NAME>, was posthumously published.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (17 October 1980): 1164" DBREF="54246">(17 October 1980): 1164</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>His correspondence with <NAME>Nancy Mitford</NAME> had reached print in 1996.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Most reviews were mocking in tone, in keeping with the late image of Waugh as a kind of Colonel Blimp. <NAME>Philip Larkin</NAME> wrote that to be one of his correspondents <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one would have to have a nursery nickname and be a member of <ORGNAME>White&apos;s</ORGNAME> [a gentlemen&apos;s club], a <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Roman Catholic</ORGNAME>, a high-born lady or an old <ORGNAME STANDARD="Eton College">Etonian</ORGNAME> novelist.</QUOTE></RRESPONSES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><DIV2><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">Yet at Waugh&apos;s death <NAME STANDARD="Larkin, Philip">Larkin</NAME> had written: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">It&apos;s very hard for me to imagine a world without Evelyn Waugh&mdash;he was one of the few really good living writers, &amp; is a great loss.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brennan 186" DBREF="65806">186</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Mount, Frederick. Living with Monsters. 2010.</SOURCE><SOURCE>ODNB.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Stovel, Bruce.</SOURCE><SOURCE>TLS Archive.</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>